’s conceptual linkage between general opposition-to-motion forces and the particular case of friction. [Data: Relationships (1170); Entities (155, 947)]\"},{\"summary\":\"Net force framing connects motion outcomes to the balance between applied and resistive forces\",\"explanation\":\"The entity “NET FORCE” is described as the overall force after combining applied forces and resistive forces; when the net force is zero, motion does not change (no movement or no acceleration), while a nonzero net force corresponds to an unbalanced force that can change motion. This gives the community a basic mechanics scaffold for interpreting when friction prevents motion versus when motion occurs. [Data: Entities (948); Relationships (1169)]\\n\\nIn the “FRICTION” description, friction is also said to counterbalance an applied force such that, when friction matches the applied force in magnitude (opposite direction), the net force becomes zero and the object can remain at rest (or not accelerate). This ties the friction concept directly into the net force framework used elsewhere in the network. [Data: Entities (155, 948)]\"},{\"summary\":\"Bicycle braking example operationalizes friction as a stopping mechanism\",\"explanation\":\"The entity “BRAKING OF A BICYCLE USING BRAKE PADS” describes a stopping process where rubber brake pads are pressed against the wheel rim to generate friction, slowing and stopping the wheel’s rotation and bringing the bicycle to rest. This provides a concrete, familiar instance of friction being intentionally increased to control motion. [Data: Entities (1060); Relationships (1387)]\\n\\nThe relationship explicitly states that bicycle braking relies on friction between rubber brake pads and the wheel rim to stop the bicycle, linking an applied technology example back to the central “FRICTION” node and illustrating friction’s useful role in controlled deceleration. [Data: Relationships (1387); Entities (1060, 155)]\"},{\"summary\":\"Disc braking in moto